  "prompt": "Why are Hela cells immortal?",
  "response": "HeLa cells are considered \"immortal\" because they can divide an unlimited number of times under the right laboratory conditions, unlike normal human cells, which have a finite lifespan. This unique characteristic is due to several factors:\n\n1. **Telomerase Activity**:  \n   HeLa cells express the enzyme **telomerase**, which prevents the shortening of telomeres. Telomeres are protective caps at the ends of chromosomes that shorten with each cell division. In most normal cells, telomere shortening eventually leads to cellular senescence or death. However, telomerase in HeLa cells continually extends telomeres, allowing the cells to bypass this limitation and divide indefinitely.\n\n2. **Cancer Origin**:  \n   HeLa cells were derived from a cervical cancer biopsy taken from Henrietta Lacks in 1951. Cancer cells often acquire mutations that disrupt normal cell cycle regulation, allowing them to proliferate uncontrollably. These mutations contribute to the immortality of HeLa cells.\n\n3. **Genetic Instability**:  \n   HeLa cells have a highly abnormal and unstable genome, with numerous chromosomal abnormalities and mutations. These genetic changes often include alterations in oncogenes (genes that promote cell growth) and tumor suppressor genes (genes that inhibit uncontrolled cell division), further enabling their immortal growth.\n\n4. **Adaptation to Laboratory Conditions**:  \n   HeLa cells have been cultured in laboratories for decades, allowing them to adapt to in vitro conditions. This selective pressure has likely enhanced their ability to survive and proliferate indefinitely.\n\nWhile HeLa cells' immortality has made them invaluable for scientific research, it also highlights their unique, cancer-like properties, which differ significantly from normal human cells.",
